{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610248"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:57:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:57:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16147"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16147"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.16,0.04,0.61,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8838"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64086"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8838"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49517"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9888"},{"type":"tags","id":"9897"},{"type":"tags","id":"9924"},{"type":"tags","id":"10623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21077"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64086"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following respiratory parameters is significantly increased during normal pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forced expiratory volume in one second","Functional residual capacity","Peak expiratory flow rate","Minute ventilation","Total lung capacity"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, there are several important respiratory physiological adaptations. \u003Cstrong\u003EMinute ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E increases by approximately 40% due to progesterone-mediated stimulation of respiratory drive. This leads to a compensated respiratory alkalosis, which is normal in pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForced expiratory volume in one second\u003C/strong\u003E (FEV1) remains essentially unchanged during pregnancy. The mechanics of forced expiration are not significantly affected by the gravid state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunctional residual capacity\u003C/strong\u003E actually decreases by about 20% due to elevation of the diaphragm by the enlarging uterus. This reduction can predispose pregnant women to early airway closure during normal breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeak expiratory flow rate\u003C/strong\u003E shows minimal change during pregnancy. While there may be some variation, it is not significantly different from the non-pregnant state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal lung capacity\u003C/strong\u003E remains relatively unchanged during pregnancy. While the diaphragm is elevated, there is compensatory broadening of the thoracic cage and increased thoracic circumference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important respiratory changes in pregnancy include increased tidal volume, decreased residual volume, and increased oxygen consumption. The increased minute ventilation helps meet the increased metabolic demands of pregnancy and facilitates carbon dioxide transfer across the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Physiological changes in pregnancy include increased tidal volume and minute ventilation, with relatively unchanged spirometric parameters.","Progesterone-mediated hyperventilation in pregnancy leads to a compensated respiratory alkalosis.","The diaphragm is elevated in pregnancy but total lung capacity remains relatively unchanged due to broadening of the thoracic cage."],"references":["Soma-Pillay P, Nelson-Piercy C, Tolppanen H, Mebazaa A. Physiological changes in pregnancy. Cardiovasc J Afr. 2016 Mar-Apr;27(2):89-94. doi: 10.5830/CVJA-2016-021. PMID: 27213856; PMCID: PMC4928162","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49517"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16147"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49517"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T22:00:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T22:01:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8838"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64086"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":nul